Banco de Oro, Manila Electric: Philippine Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-01T01:04:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/banco-de-oro-manila-electric-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and prices are as of yesterday in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.8 percent to
3,766.73.    Banco de Oro Unibank Inc . (BDO PM): The largest Philippine
bank by assets said its 2010 net income grew 46 percent to 8.8
billion pesos ($202 million), topping its 8.1 billion peso
profit forecast, the lender said in an e-mailed statement. The
stock gained 0.9 percent to 46.90 pesos.    Manila Electric Co . (MER PM): The largest Philippine power
retailer may spend $2 billion to $2.3 billion for an estimated
1,500 megawatts of power generating capacity it plans to put up
from 2012 to 2016, Chief Operating Officer Oscar Reyes said. The
utility said profit rose to 9.7 billion pesos last year from 6
billion pesos in 2009. The stock declined 2.9 percent to 231
pesos.    Metro Pacific Investments Corp . (MPI PM): The Philippine
unit of Hong Kong’s First Pacific Co. will bid for government
projects and assets from tollroad, railways and airports, Metro
Pacific Chairman Manuel Pangilinan said. The stock fell 0.3
percent to 3.43 pesos.    Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co . (TEL PM): Profit at
the nation’s biggest company by market value rose last year from
2009 and that it “won’t disappoint,” Chairman Manuel
Pangilinan said, declining to comment whether the company met
its target. Sales in January likely slowed from a year earlier,
he said. The company is scheduled to release earnings today. The
stock lost 2.8 percent to 2,160 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in  Manila  at 
